SIMPLE: succinct
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Succinct
<hw>Suc*cinct"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>succinctus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>succingere</ets> to gird below or
from below, to tuck up; <ets>sub + cingere</ets> to gird. Cf.
<er>Cincture</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Girded or tucked up; bound;
drawn tightly together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His habit fit for speed <qex>succinct</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Compressed into a narrow compass; brief;
concise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let all your precepts be <qex>succinct</qex> and clear.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The shortest and most <qex>succinct</qex> model that ever grasped
all the needs and necessities of mankind.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Short; brief; concise; summary; compendious;
laconic; terse.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Suc*cinct"ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Suc*cinct"ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Succinic</ent>⟦br⟧
